    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-10-18T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-10-18T03:00:00-05:00" n="780"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d780">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/6490: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Hong Kong</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Donovan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hong Kong</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-18T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 18, 1937—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 18—7:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Referring to my telegram September 28, noon, Hong Kong and Shanghai Bank state
                    that shipments of Chinese Government silver to London are continuing at the rate
                    of from $15,000,000 to $25,000,000 per week. They deny reports that any Chinese
                    Government silver has been shipped from Hong Kong to Singapore or Manila.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Nanking, paraphrase by mail to Singapore, Manila.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Donovan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
